column1: #Text=Athletics concludes at London Paralympics with the marathon
#Text=Christie Dawes of Australia finishes fifth in the women 's T54 marathon while setting an Oceania recordImage : Laura Hale .

#Text=Yesterday , on the final day of competition , athletics concluded at the London Paralympics with the running and wheeling of the marathon for the men 's T12 , T46 and T54 , and the women 's T54 .

#Text=Spain and Great Britain both had a gold and a silver medal , Brazil and the United States had a gold each , Switzerland had a silver and a bronze medal , Colombia had a silver medal , and Tunisia , Australia and Belarus each had a bronze medal .
#Text=Alberto Suarez Laso of Spain set a world and European record in the T12 marathon with a time of 2:24:50 .
#Text=In the same event , Tunisian Abderrahim Zhiou set an African record with a time of 2:26:56 and Colomobian Elkin Alonso Serna Moreno set an Americas record with a time of 2:26:39 .
#Text=Despite failing to get a medal , Japanese Masahiro Okamura set an Asian record with a time of 2:28:51 .
#Text=In the women 's T54 event , Australian Christie Dawes set an Oceania record with a time of 1:49:37 .
#Text=Great Britain 's gold medal was earned by David Weir , and was Weir 's fourth gold medal earned in the London .
#Text=This put Weir at the top of the individual gold medal count for London alongside Raymond Martin of the United States .
#Text=Tatyana McFadden of the United States had a chance at four gold medals in London , but was unable to seriously compete after a pair of tire punctures mid-race that seriously slowed her down .
#Text=McFadden conveyed her experiences in the race to the media , saying , " At 18 or 19 miles it went again , this always seems to happen to me in London .
